I know you intend nothing bad here, and you've done nothing bad.

But nonetheless, speaking as a Jew, I would appreciate it if, unless
it violates parallelism or otherwise grates in a sentence, posters
could use "Jew" instead of "Jewish person", and Jews instead of Jewish
people.

So many people have used Jew as something bad, something hateful, that
those people have given much of the Western world the impression that
Jew is a dirty word, and even people of good will have been avoiding
using it.  Even some Jews pick up this speech habit.

For example, I've seen or heard people say things like, "A Swede, a
Norwegian, and a Jewish person".   That's not the case in the sentence
I'm reacting to, but I didn't want to pass up this opportunity to
raise this subject.

I think that avoiding the word Jew when it fits the sentence, no
matter what is intended when doing so, gives subtle confirmation of
the opinion of the haters, that Jew is a dirty word.  The way to end
that seems to me to be to use the word as much as possible in places
where Jewish person could be used instead.

I'm not suggesting redoing the entire sentence, for example, redoing a
different phrase into "a Swedish person, a Norwegian person, and a
Jew".  That would violate parallelism and I would not recommend that.

If you doubt that my observation is accurate, just count.  People are
more willing to use Jews than Jew, but it is still uncommon compared
to "Jewish people".

I'm not claiming to speak for other Jews here, but when I have
discussed it with other Jews on quite a few occasions, no one has said
I was wrong.

Somewhat related is a post I read on Usenet where someone thought that
Yid was an insulting word (so, being a nice guy, he had avoided using
it).  I replied to him and said that it may be used as an insult by a
jackass, but the word was not insulting at all.  It is Yiddish for
Jew.

