Context is always nice.
OED has "smoucher" from the verb "smouch" - to kiss, from the 16th Century.
We'd expect to see the "smooch" spelling these days. And under the "smooch"
spelling, OED has further meanings of the verb - to "sully or dirty" from
C17 but latterly (C19) U.S. and to "sneak, creep ... or prowl" from early
C20 as a variant on "mooch" or "mouch" which is used for loafing, stealing
and pilfering and even, in a slang usage dated to 1857:

5. intr. 'To sponge, to slink away and allow others to pay for your
entertainment' (Barrère &amp; Leland Dict. Slang).
1857 'Ducange Anglicus' Vulgar Tongue 13 Mouch, v., to go about sponging
on your friends.

And we all know Minnie the Moocher ...

--
John Dean
