If a person lives or works in a milieu in which the term "Jew" is
used in a derogatory sense by some people, that person may tend to
avoid the term because listeners might interpret it as insulting to
a Jew or Jews.

It can be a bit nerve-jangling for such a person to switch to using
"Jew" in a straightforward sense.

Some individuals might be concerned that the practice of using "Jew"
straightforwardly here might accidentally carry over into
circumstances in which it would perceived as being derogatory.

On the infrequent occasions in this ng[1] when it is relevant to
refer to someone as a Jew I will do just that. However, I will tend
to hesitate while I consider where I am before using the word.

I'm not arguing against your plea for the use of "Jew". I'm just
pointing out that it can be genuinely difficult for some
individuals.

[1] And in the other ng: alt.usage.english.

--
Peter Duncanson, UK
(in alt.english.usage)
